        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>San Francisco</placeName> <date>March 26&#47;54</date></p>
			<p>To</p>
			<p><sic><addressee>Isaacs Lesser Esqre</addressee></sic></p>
			<p><placeName>371 Walnut St. Philadelphia</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">I arrived in this city from <placeName>Auburn</placeName><lb/> about two weeks back&#44; have seen your agent<lb/> <persName>Mr C Myers</persName> who kindly give me the Occident<lb/> containing the portion of my letter.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I have used my endeavours in forwarding<lb/> your <sic>enterpriseing</sic> work the Bible&#44; which<lb/> I must say is a Credit to you&#44; and trust<lb/> will prove productive for your labours.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">In regard to further Information<lb/> respecting the Jews in <placeName>China</placeName>&#44; I have had an<lb/> Interview with <persName>Mr Spear</persName> of whom I spoke of<lb/> in my last&#44; he <sic>his</sic> not the Gent who was<lb/> in <placeName>China</placeName> in my time&#44; he has only been in<lb/> <placeName>Canton</placeName> three years and not out of it till he<lb/> come to this country&#44; as he said to me we who<lb/> reside at <placeName>Canton</placeName> can have but little com&#45;<lb/>&#45;munication with the Chinese in consequence<lb/> of its being unsafe to go out into the streets&#44; he<lb/> also says that he never heard or read of any such<lb/> sect as Jews &#38;c in <placeName>China</placeName> he is only acquainted with<lb/> the Canton Dialect&#44; in the Occident of <date>January</date><lb/> Page 514 you propose to send a person duly qualified<lb/> to <placeName>Shanghai</placeName> to open communication with<lb/> the people of <placeName>Kai&#45;fong&#45;foo</placeName>&#44; that proposition</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p><sic>his</sic> highly <sic>esential</sic> as that <hi rend="underline">must</hi> be the first step. To begin about there to carry out the object in <add>&#63;</add><lb/> then follow the plan of the <sic>Jesuites</sic> which is to<lb/> establish posts of communications in every<lb/> district from <placeName>Shanghai</placeName> to the place <sic>wher</sic> our supp<lb/>&#45;osed <sic>Bretherin</sic> are to be found&#44; this is to be done by<lb/> feeing<add>&#63;</add> the officer of each district then they will<lb/> pass the letters of <sic>corrospondance</sic>&#44; and <sic>verry</sic><lb/> probable pass a <sic>foreignor</sic> through&#44; as let a <sic>foreignor</sic><lb/> Disguise himself ever so much the Chinese can<lb/> Discover him&#44; which if such should be the case<lb/> the officer of the district can torment him in a most<lb/> Barbarous manner for any length of time and<lb/> when he thinks proper he can send him back<lb/> through the same districts as he come to his first<lb/> starting place&#44; and then the isolated Traveller<lb/> cannot have any redress from his Government&#44;<lb/> a Little money works wonders among the China officials<lb/> <sic>therefor</sic> I am still of the same opinion that the<lb/> <sic>Obsticals</sic> are to be over come in communicating<lb/> with the people of <placeName>Kai&#45;fong&#45;foo</placeName>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><sic>if</sic> the people in the <placeName><sic>atlantic</sic></placeName> are going to send<lb/> out a mission and they have confidence enough<lb/> in me I should have no objection of being one<lb/> of the parties for that mission to <placeName>Shanghai</placeName>&#44; provided<lb/> that I was paid for going out there&#44; any persons<lb/> which they may send if they should come by way<lb/> of <placeName>California</placeName> I shall be most happy to give them<lb/> all the information that lays in my power as with<lb/> one hour conversation with them I should be able</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>to enlighten them more than writing six sheets of<lb/> paper full about <placeName>China</placeName>. Questions would bring<lb/> things to my memory <sic>wher</sic> other wise I cannot<lb/> think of them and I would not have any thing<lb/> which I may write or repeat go before the public<lb/> but that which I know to be the Truth.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I will conclude by wishing you<lb/> every success in your undertakings<lb/> &#38; <sic>Belive</sic> me to be yours</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">Samuel H. Cohen</persName></p>
			<p>care of <persName>B Keesing</persName> <placeName>Box 488 Post Office</placeName></p>
          
